---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { withBase } from '../../paths';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="World | Via Occulta"
  description="The Via Occulta world premise: hidden sacred roads, failing shrines, guild restoration, and the first region called The Pilgrim Verge."
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">World premise</p>
      <h1>The old roads have vanished from the maps.</h1>
      <p>
        For centuries, the surface kingdoms survived by traveling the Viae Occultae: hidden sacred roads that opened through shrines, caves, drowned chapels, forest gates, sewers, market doors, guild cellars, and sealed underways under the correct rite.
      </p>
      <div class="link-row">
        <a class="text-link" href={withBase('/world/the-pilgrim-verge')}>Explore The Pilgrim Verge</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell split">
      <div class="summary-panel panel">
        <p class="eyebrow">The quiet collapse</p>
        <h3>The world is being rerouted from underneath itself.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Crystals no longer hold their light.</li>
          <li>Trade routes break without warning.</li>
          <li>Wells open into catacombs.</li>
          <li>Chapel doors lead to rooms that should not exist.</li>
          <li>Monsters appear from inside the road-network itself.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Via Occulta is dangerous but not hopeless. Its tone is ancient, ritualistic, lonely, guild-driven, and closer to a cursed pilgrimage than a standard heroic conquest.
        </p>
        <p>
          The central fantasy is not to become the chosen one. It is to find the hidden road, survive what guards it, bring back proof, and help the town remember how to use it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">The failed compact</p>
      <h2>Three powers once kept the hidden roads stable.</h2>
      <div class="three-up">
        <article class="info-card panel">
          <h3>The Shrine Orders</h3>
          <p>
            Keepers of old rites, road prayers, names, bells, and threshold customs. Their knowledge opens paths, but many of their rites are incomplete or corrupted.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="info-card panel">
          <h3>The Guild Houses</h3>
          <p>
            Practical maintainers of exchange, workshops, charters, tools, and road infrastructure. They turn dangerous discoveries into usable life.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="info-card panel">
          <h3>The Crystal Courts</h3>
          <p>
            Boundary keepers tied to court relics, checkpoints, archives, sealed thresholds, and old road law.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell split">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Hidden road logic</p>
        <h2>A road can be a place, a rite, or a repaired object.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="path-list">
        <span>chapel basements</span>
        <span>forest glades</span>
        <span>sewer gates</span>
        <span>cave mouths</span>
        <span>old shrines</span>
        <span>moonlit bridges</span>
        <span>market cellars</span>
        <span>guild-hall doors</span>
        <span>grave paths</span>
        <span>ruined towers</span>
        <span>monster dens</span>
        <span>remembered names</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
